it is the combination of both new and constructor, the reason behind allowing the constructor calling in main method.
if suppose,
create a Constructor:

**public SampleTest(){}**

calling it from main method:

**Scenario 1:** if i directly calling that constructor from main method without new keyword::

        SampleTest();

**Result 1:** it is throwing the compile time exception **&quot;The method SampleTest() is undefined for the type SampleTest&quot;**

**Scenario 2:** if i created a method named SampleTest() in that class as shown below(which has return type as void, as we don&#39;t have return types for constructors):

      public void SampleTest() {}

      public static void main(String[] args){
        SampleTest();
      }

**Result 2:** it is throwing the compile time exception **&quot;Cannot make a static reference to the non-static method SampleTest() from the type SampleTest&quot;**

**Scenario 3:** now if add new keyword before constructor calling as shown below:

      new  SampleTest();

**Result 3:** so now only with the combination of **new** operator with **constructor** calling is allowed in main method, with out showing any exception.

So finally, the reason behind the constructor calling from the main method is the combination of new and constructor. otherwise it considers the constructor as any other instance method, throws exceptions as in Result 1 and 2.

