answers.body_markdown:
Angular has nothing to do with this is something related to [Is JavaScript a pass-by-reference or pass-by-value language?][1]

So in java script when you copy primitive types (number, string, etc.) value will be copied not the reference itself, but in case of objects reference will be copied and change will reflect to parent object as well.

Below is interesting example for both reference type and value type

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    var obj={a:10};
    var copyObj=obj;
    obj.a=12;
    console.log(obj.a);//example of reference type you can see the output will be 12;

    var a=10;
    var b=a;
    b=12;
    console.log(a);//example of value type here output is still 10

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;


[One more related SO here][2]

There are many ways to communicate from child to parent for example you can use **[@Output][3]**,**shared service**,**subject**,**eventemitter** etc

[Here is an SO ans related to child parent communication][4]


  [1]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/518000/is-javascript-a-pass-by-reference-or-pass-by-value-language
  [2]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/40433889/hard-copy-vs-shallow-copy-javascript
  [3]: https://blog.kevinchisholm.com/angular/child-parent-communication-output/
  [4]: https://stackoverflow.com/a/51770232/5621827

